status: MARC21-007: Kind of material of sound recording
Kind of material used in the manufacture of sound recordings (both instantaneous and mass-produced).

definition (en): Lacquer coated, but the base material on which the lacquer is applied is not identified.

scope note (en): used for items such as memovox discs.

definition (en): Acetate base with a ferrous oxide coating.
scope note (en): May include acetate tape and belts, such as magnabelts.

definition (en): Glass disc base with a lacquer coating.
Aluminum disc base with a lacquer coating.

scope note (en): Includes the earliest cylinders, which were made of tinfoil, and aluminum transcription discs with no coating, as well as wire and metal tape.

definition (en): Made of plastic base with a metal coating.
scope note (en): The metal part of such an item is often a thin layer applied to the plastic base. Includes compact audio discs (CDs).
Also includes mylar, polyester and vinyl materials. Since the 1950s, commercial or mass-produced sound recordings on 16, 33 1/3, and 45 rpm discs, cassettes, and cartridges are made of plastic.

preferred label (en): paper with lacquer or ferrous oxide
definition (en): Paper or cardboard disc, tape, or cylinder base with a lacquer or ferrous oxide coating.

scope note (en): Most commercial or mass-produced 78 rpm discs are made of shellac.

definition (en): Kind of material used in the manufacture of the item is not known.

scope note (en): Most instantaneous cylinders were made of wax.

definition (en): Kind of material other than lacquer coating, cellulose nitrate, acetate tape with ferrous oxide. glass with lacquer, aluminum with lacquer, metal, plastic with metal, plastic, paper with lacquer or ferrous oxide, shellac, wax.
